<subSubSection id="99F2651FFFBAFFE0FCCCFCBB4DD6FA15" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D1573694FFBAFFE0FCCCFCBB4D1BFBF5" blockId="11.[801,1452,876,1509]" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis id="E39CEA86FFBAFFE0FCCCFCBB4DC7FC75" box="[839,1189,876,900]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">
Notes. – 
<taxonomicName id="16E84D17FFBAFFE0FC23FCBA4DC7FC75" box="[936,1189,876,900]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Polypodiaceae" genus="Polypodium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spinulosum">Polypodium spinulosum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
was based on a sterile specimen that was erroneously supposed to originate from Java and an illustration. This name does in fact represent an endemic 
<taxonomicName id="16E84D17FFBAFFE0FC0BFC1B4A85FC15" box="[896,999,973,996]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Proteaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Proteales" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">
<emphasis id="E39CEA86FFBAFFE0FC0BFC1B4A85FC15" box="[896,999,973,996]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">Proteaceae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion id="132CF876FFBAFFE0FBAEFC1B4D86FC15" box="[1061,1252,972,996]" country="Australia" name="Western Australia" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">Western Australia</collectingRegion>
: 
<taxonomicName id="16E84D17FFBAFFE0FB65FC1A4CC9FC15" box="[1262,1451,972,996]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Proteaceae" genus="Synaphea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Proteales" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spinulosa">
<emphasis id="E39CEA86FFBAFFE0FB65FC1A4CC9FC15" box="[1262,1451,972,996]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">Synaphea spinulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="B5794B65FFBAFFE0FCA1FC3B4A9EFBF5" author="MERRILL" box="[810,1020,1004,1028]" firstAuthor="MERRILL" journalOrPublisher="Proc. Linn. Soc. New South Wales" page="354" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" pagination="354" part="44" refId="ref9939" refString="MERRILL, E. D. (1919). On the identity of Polypodium spinulosum. Proc. Linn. Soc. New South Wales 44: 354." title="On the identity of Polypodium spinulosum" type="journal article" year="1919">MERRILL, 1919: 354</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B5794B65FFBAFFE0FB8CFC3A4D0CFBF5" author="MERRILL, E. D." box="[1031,1134,1004,1028]" journalOrPublisher="Philippine J. Sci." pageId="11" pageNumber="104" pagination="329 - 388" part="19" refId="ref9969" refString="MERRILL, E. D. (1921). A review of the new species of plants proposed by N. L. Burman in his Flora Indica. Philippine J. Sci. 19: 329 - 388." title="A review of the new species of plants proposed by N. L. Burman in his Flora Indica" type="journal article" year="1921">1920: 347</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D1573694FFBAFFE0FCCCFBDA4D33FB95" blockId="11.[801,1452,876,1509]" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">
<bibRefCitation id="B5794B65FFBAFFE0FCCCFBDA4D7EFBD5" author="GEORGE" box="[839,1052,1036,1060]" editor="ORCHARD, A. E. &amp; P. M. MCCARTHY" firstAuthor="GEORGE" page="277" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" pagination="271 - 315" part="16" refId="ref9403" refString="GEORGE, A. S. (1995). Proteaceae, Synaphea. In: ORCHARD, A. E. &amp; P. M. MCCARTHY (ed.), Fl. Australia 16: 271 - 315." title="Proteaceae, Synaphea" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Fl. Australia" year="1995">GEORGE (1995: 277)</bibRefCitation>
cited the single specimen of original material extant in G-PREL as 
<typeStatus id="0E538836FFBAFFE0FBF8FBFA4DB1FBB5" box="[1139,1235,1068,1092]" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">holotype</typeStatus>
. This implicit lectotypification is accepted here.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D1573694FFBAFFE0FCCCFBBA4DD6FA15" blockId="11.[801,1452,876,1509]" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">
<bibRefCitation id="B5794B65FFBAFFE0FCCCFBBA4D68FB75" author="GEORGE" box="[839,1034,1132,1156]" firstAuthor="GEORGE" journalOrPublisher="Western Australian Naturalist" page="177" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" pagination="173 - 178" part="11" refId="ref9330" refString="GEORGE, A. S. (1971). The plants seen and collected in North-Western Australia by William Dampier. Western Australian Naturalist 11: 173 - 178." title="The plants seen and collected in North-Western Australia by William Dampier" type="journal article" year="1971">GEORGE (1971: 177</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B5794B65FFBAFFE0FB9FFBBA4D04FB75" author="GEORGE" box="[1044,1126,1132,1156]" firstAuthor="GEORGE" journalOrPublisher="Special Publ. Soc. Bibliogr. Nat. Hist." page="53" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" pagination="53 - 59" part="1" refId="ref9361" refString="GEORGE, A. S. (1981). The genus Banksia L. f. - a case history in Australian botany. Special Publ. Soc. Bibliogr. Nat. Hist. 1: 53 - 59." title="The genus Banksia L. f. - a case history in Australian botany" type="journal article" year="1981">1981: 53</bibRefCitation>
) suggested that the 
<typeStatus id="0E538836FFBAFFE0FAB2FBBB4C04FB74" box="[1337,1382,1133,1157]" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">type</typeStatus>
specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="16E84D17FFBAFFE0FCF5FB5B4D7EFB55" box="[894,1052,1165,1188]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncata">
<emphasis id="E39CEA86FFBAFFE0FCF5FB5B4D7EFB55" box="[894,1052,1165,1188]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">Acacia truncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above 
<taxonomicName id="16E84D17FFBAFFE0FB12FB5A4C11FB55" box="[1177,1395,1164,1188]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Pteridaceae" genus="Adiantum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polypodiales" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncatum">
<emphasis id="E39CEA86FFBAFFE0FB12FB5A4C11FB55" box="[1177,1395,1164,1188]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">Adiantum truncatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="16E84D17FFBAFFE0FCAAFB7A4A83FB35" box="[801,993,1196,1220]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Proteaceae" genus="Synaphea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Proteales" pageId="11" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spinulosa">
<emphasis id="E39CEA86FFBAFFE0FCAAFB7A4A83FB35" box="[801,993,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">Synaphea spinulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have been collected in 1697 during the VOC expedition conducted by Wilhelm Vlaming. Thus one of the oldest collections made by Europeans in 
<collectingCountry id="A9FF7604FFBAFFE0FB71FB3A4C3FFAF5" box="[1274,1373,1260,1284]" name="Australia" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">Australia</collectingCountry>
. Vlaming’s ship was the first Dutch ship to stop in 
<collectingCountry id="A9FF7604FFBAFFE0FB74FADA4C02FAD5" box="[1279,1376,1292,1316]" name="Australia" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">Australia</collectingCountry>
on the way to Java. During the course of the 18th century, the VOC ships took a more direct sea road from the Cape to Java often sailing the coast of 
<collectingRegion id="132CF876FFBAFFE0FC71FABB4DA1FA75" box="[1018,1219,1388,1412]" country="Australia" name="Western Australia" pageId="11" pageNumber="104">Western Australia</collectingRegion>
before reaching Java (
<bibRefCitation id="B5794B65FFBAFFE0FCA1FA5B4ADEFA55" author="BRUIJN" box="[810,956,1420,1444]" firstAuthor="BRUIJN" journalOrPublisher="J. Southeast Asian Stud." pageId="11" pageNumber="104" pagination="251 - 265" part="11" refId="ref8828" refString="BRUIJN, J. R. (1980). Between Batavia and the Cape: Shipping Patterns of the Dutch East India Company. J. Southeast Asian Stud. 11: 251 - 265." title="Between Batavia and the Cape: Shipping Patterns of the Dutch East India Company" type="journal article" year="1980">BRUIJN, 1980</bibRefCitation>
). Those Australian specimens could also have been collected later in the mid 18th century when Kleynhoff, Pryon or van Santen travelled to Java.
</paragraph>
